#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:8
msgid "SYNOPSIS: Install LinuxFromScratch using only 1 bootable Linux-partition"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:13
msgid ""
"DESCRIPTION: If you got no spare partition to build your LFS on, you could "
"turn a file into a partition, using the so-called loop-device. The transfer "
"of the system to the root partition is a bit tricky, though."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:19
msgid ""
"PREREQUISITES: You need to have loop device support compiled into your "
"kernel (if you're unsure, run \"grep LOOP /usr/src/linux/.config\"; if the "
"last letter is y or m, the kernel compiled with that options has loop device "
"support enabled), otherwise run"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:24
msgid ""
"sed s/\\#\\ CONFIG_BLK_DEV_LOOP\\ is\\ not\\ set/CONFIG_BLK_DEV_LOOP=m/ \\ "
"usr/src/linux/.config > conf && mv conf /usr/src/linux/.config && cd "
"/usr/src/linux && make modules modules_install && insmod loop && cd /dev && "
"./MAKEDEV loop"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:31
msgid ""
"Now your kernel should have loop device support through a module. Other than "
"that, you need about 1GB (rather make it a bit more, the filesystem is "
"stored in the file as well and adds up to some MB of data) of free space on "
"your root partition (or any other partition you intend to store your loop "
"file on). The commands \"cd /dev && ./MAKEDEV loop should be omitted on "
"systems which are using devfs)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:41
msgid ""
"HINT: The following text describes the changes you have to make to the "
"normal LFS installing procedere when using only 1 bootable partition. It's "
"not complete without the LFS Book. It is just a description of the things "
"you ought to do in a different way than declared in the LFS book. It splits "
"up into 2 parts that differ from the Book: first, of course, the making of "
"partition, which is replaced by the making and setup of a loop device file, "
"and next, the deletion of the previous system due to the need of diskspace "
"for the new one and the installation and boot setup, that differs a bit, "
"too."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:48
msgid ""
"REISERFS WARNING: If you're using reiserfs, this hint is almost unusable for "
"you due to deletion errors on a recursive mounted volume with reiserfs (the "
"files will be deleted, but the space wouldn't be freed). You could still use "
"the hint to make every- thing ready for a transfer using a bootdisk/CD, but "
"don't try the \"Delete the previous System\" section or further. You've been "
"warned!"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:52
msgid ""
"RECOMMENDATION: Make yourself a bootdisk or bootCD, whatever is sufficient "
"on your system. You can prevent a lot of trouble when rebooting fails."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:57
msgid ""
"If you don't know how to make a bootdisk or bootCD, look at the hints, the "
"BLFS section about it or search for bootdisk on freshmeat. Be sure that the "
"bootdisk or -CD is able to read/write your root partition, e.g. a tomsrtbt "
"is currently not able to mount reiserfs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:59
msgid "When you come to the part of the LFS Book which is called:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:61
msgid "\"Creating a new partition\""
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:64
msgid ""
"You don't want to create a new partition! That's why you're trying to use "
"this hint. Therefore, this should be replaced with:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:66
msgid "Making a loop device file:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:70
msgid ""
"Be sure to be superuser and that you have all variables ($LFS) set up like "
"you're told in the book. Then make a file containing enough MB of nothing "
"running:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:72
msgid "dd if=/dev/zero of=/tmp/lfs.disk bs=1M count=XXX"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:80
msgid ""
"\"dd\" is short for \"disk dump\"; it will dump the contents of an device or "
"file into another device or file. We dump from input file \"/dev/zero\", so "
"everything in the new output file \"lfs.disk\" will be empty space. This "
"file /tmp/lfs.disk will become our loop device file soon. The newer versions "
"of software you use, the more space you will probably need for compiling; "
"you might want to replace XXX with 800-900 MB for LFS 2.x, 900-1000 MB for "
"LFS 3.x and 1000-1100 MB for LFS 4.x/5.x or even more to be on the safe "
"site."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:82
msgid "Setting up the loop device:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:84
msgid "You load the file you made to the loop device with the command"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:86
msgid "losetup /dev/loop0 /tmp/lfs.disk"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:89
msgid ""
"which will bind /tmp/lfs.disk to the loop device /dev/loop0; everything "
"written to /dev/loop0 will go directly into /tmp/lfs.disk."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:91
msgid "Creating a ext2 file system on the new partition:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:96
msgid ""
"We don't have a new partition. But we have our file \"lfs.disk\" (or "
"whatever you called it) on the /dev/loop0 device. So instead of creating the "
"file system on /dev/hda2 or any other partition, we're using the command on "
"the loop device our file is attached to:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:98
msgid "mke2fs /dev/loop0"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:108
msgid ""
"This will write an ext2 filesystem to our /tmp/lfs.disk file using the loop "
"device. You could also use mkreiserfs or any other filesystem that is "
"capable of handling unix-style attributes (So dosfs/vfat doesn't count, but "
"umsdos does), but be warned that a journalling filesystem like reiserfs "
"produces grossiping amounts of overhead, so prepare yourself in patience for "
"a slow installation. I hear your questions why reiserfs should be slower "
"than ext2fs at a loop device. This is because the reiserfs uses a journal "
"which is accessed every time at write accesses, so you have to write almost "
"any data twice vs. once using ext2fs."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:113
msgid ""
"If you haven't got any idea about what I was writing about the last "
"paragraph, just believe me using ext2fs is the best method. If your main "
"system uses a journalling filesystem, the data is safe anyway, because "
"lfs.disk will be included in the journal, too."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:115
msgid "Mounting the new partition:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:117
msgid "mount /dev/loop0 /mnt/lfs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:120
msgid ""
"Instead of mount e.g. /dev/hda2 to /mnt/lfs, we're using our loop "
"device. From now on, the installation may proceed as in the book."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:126
msgid ""
"Before entering the chrooted environment (which usually happens in Chapter "
"6), you can safely put the sources in your /home/lfs directory and unpack "
"them directly there. When entering the chrooted environment, you can reduce "
"the needed space by unpacking the sources from another login in which you do "
"not enter the chrooted environment."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:129
msgid ""
"Of course you can delete every packagedir (even the kernel) after installa- "
"tion, unless the book tells otherwise."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:131
msgid "Halting the Building of LFS:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:137
msgid ""
"So you found that building LFS using this hint takes too long to do it in "
"one pass? Never mind. All you have to do is save the system in a secure "
"state so you can shut down safely. When in chroot'ed mode, first umount "
"everything that's mounted to /mnt/lfs, then get every shell away from "
"/mnt/lfs and umount /mnt/lfs itself."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:139
msgid "Then exit the chrooted mode. Now unmount the lfs \"partition\":"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:146
msgid ""
"umount /dev/shm umount /dev/pts umount /proc exit # the chrooted environment "
"cd # get out of /mnt/lfs umount /mnt/lfs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:148
msgid "Now you can safely set back the loop devices:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:150 origin/one-partition-hint.txt:322
msgid "losetup -d /dev/loop0"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:153
msgid ""
"Now you can safely shut down your system. When you start again, you need to "
"perform those steps \"backwards\", like you already did in the beginning:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:156
msgid "losetup lfs.disk /dev/loop0 mount /dev/loop0 /mnt/lfs"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:159
msgid ""
"Now chroot and mount proc if necessary (use the commands you find in the LFS "
"Book, they may differ from version to version)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:162
msgid ""
"The following steps are quite the same. The only differences starts again "
"when you want to make this drive bootable:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:164
msgid "Making the LFS System bootable:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:169
msgid ""
"A thought on making the kernel in LFS: why reconfigure everything? Even if "
"you've got an old kernel, most of the things you've chosen (or not)  during "
"kernel configuration have not changed a bit. You could fasten up this if "
"instead of"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:171
msgid "make menuconfig"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:173
msgid "using out of the chroot'ed environment:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:177
msgid "cp /usr/src/linux/.config $LFS/usr/src/linux <enter chroot> make oldconfig"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:181
msgid ""
"Now you only get asked on the things that weren't configured with your new "
"kernel (which should be somewhat less work than choosing every menu). If "
"you're unsure, you could still check it with \"make menuconfig\"."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:186
msgid ""
"Make your kernel and grub (or lilo, if you are using an version < 5.x) in "
"the chroot'ed environment as described in the LFS book. Don't try to start "
"grub or lilo now! Stop here! I hope you're still in the chroot'ed "
"environment, other- wise go back there."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:189
msgid ""
"The only bootable partition you've got is the one your current distro is "
"running on."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:192
msgid ""
"If you want to use the /tmp/lfs.disk file for anything else than installing "
"LFS over your distribution, you'll probably not need the following part."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:195
msgid ""
"You're about to install LFS on the partition, deleting the distro. But "
"before you get started, read the following warning carefully:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:196
#, no-wrap
msgid "-------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:198
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"               Do yourself a real big favour and get a bootdisk! \n"
"-------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:203
msgid ""
"If you delete your distribution and have a power failure, you would lose "
"your whole system (including the lfs.disk file that you can't access anymore "
"without a bootable linux system unless you get a bootdisk)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:205
msgid "Mounting the main partition:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:208
msgid ""
"Mount the main partition to \"/mnt\" in the chroot'ed environment suggesting "
"your main partition is /dev/hda1, otherwise fill in what is necessary:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:210
msgid "mount /dev/hda1 /mnt"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:219
msgid ""
"The main partition is now mounted to a directory in a file attached to a "
"block device which is mounted on the main partition (that is mounted to a "
"directory and so on...). This is a really nice example for recursion. And "
"this could get another nice example of an almost infinite loop (depending on "
"your harddisk's size), if you try to copy everything to mount. Or an "
"destructive loop, if you try to delete everything in /mnt (because this also "
"holds the file currently working as your root environment). If you're asking "
"what I'm talking about, never mind, just follow the next instructions very, "
"very carefully."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:221
msgid "Making sure init finds his getty:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:225
msgid ""
"If you know what I'm talking about, you could go straight to the following "
"paragraph. Anyone else may read the explanation: \"init\" is the process "
"that is started by the kernel to start everything else during the bootup."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:235
msgid ""
"Everything else, that is, all calls that are in /etc/inittab. In this "
"inittab, you should find some version program getty, for example agetty or "
"mgetty, but maybe only getty. This program is used to load the programs that "
"allow you to login into your system. Now imagine you delete the whole old "
"stuff including the old getty. Imagine further the LFS's agetty is different "
"from the distro's version, or in a different directory (Debian, for example, "
"uses getty). The inittab should remain in the memory. Init would try (on "
"your next login) to use a getty that's not there, meaning you wouldn't be "
"able anymore to login into your system, which could be fatal in the current "
"state."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:240
msgid ""
"Before you logout of the chroot'ed system you should be sure that the init "
"process will find the version of getty named in the inittab, otherwise you "
"would be unable to access the system anymore and need the the bootdisk! A "
"short"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:242
msgid "cat /mnt/etc/inittab | grep getty"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:246
msgid ""
"shows wether your previous system is using getty, agetty, mgetty or any "
"other version possible. If it's using any other version than agetty (that's "
"what Linux From Scratch is using), you should do a symlink like"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:248
msgid "ln -s /sbin/agetty /sbin/<the distro's getty version>"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:250
msgid "Now you can safely replace the old system."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:252
msgid "Deleting the previous System:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:262
msgid ""
"To repeat the previous warning: That DOESN'T WORK well with reiserfs. I've "
"double-checked if the issue would be resolved in the current reiserfs "
"version, but the result was negative: the deletion of recursive mounted file "
"systems leaves the emptied space unusable, because it's not cleared in the "
"journal! So don't try the next steps if you are using reiserfs! If you are "
"using an ext3 partition, you may mount it as ext2 and covert it back after "
"you copied the new LFS to your main partition. Anyone using reiserfs should "
"create a boot-CD with the new LFS in a .tar.gz file. You'll find a short "
"description at the end of this hint"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:265
msgid ""
"You'll have to get the main partition entirely clean from everything that is "
"not /mnt, /tmp/lfs.disk and proc, which holds another file system:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:270
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"for dirname in `ls -1 /mnt | sed -e /tmp/d -e /proc/d -e /mnt/d`; do \n"
" rm -r /mnt/$dirname; done &&\n"
"for filename in `ls /mnt/tmp | sed s/lfs.disk//`; do \n"
" rm $filename; done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:274
msgid ""
"You may omit other directories at will by adding \"-e /<directory>/d\" to "
"the first sed command. The second line is only needed if you want to clear "
"the /tmp directory, too."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:278
msgid ""
"Now the partition should be clean enough for copying the LFS system. If you "
"want to keep other files and are not so sure about your shell scripting "
"skills, better delete all unnecessary files by hand (don't touch /tmp, /proc "
"or /mnt)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:280
msgid "Copying the system to the root partition:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:284
msgid ""
"Now we may copy the new system. Everything but the /mnt directory, to which "
"the device that we are filling with LFS is mounted and the directory /proc, "
"in which are dynamic files written by the kernel."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:287
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"for dirname in `ls -1 / | sed -e /mnt/d -e /proc/d -e /tmp/d`; do \n"
" cp -a $dirname /mnt; done\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:289 origin/one-partition-hint.txt:306
msgid "Command explanations"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:291
msgid "cp -a ... /mnt:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:295
msgid ""
"copies in \"archive\" mode, so the whole directories are copies with their "
"content and all subdirs and all filemodes are kept, if possible. For the for "
"...; do; done constructions look at the previous command explanation."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:298
msgid ""
"Now the LFS is on your primary partition logout of the chroot'ed environment "
"into the new system. Now you can perform grub/lilo and this stuff."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:304
msgid ""
"logout (or exit)  cd / umount /mnt/lfs/proc umount /mnt/lfs losetup -d "
"/dev/loop0"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:308
msgid "logout/exit:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:310
msgid "Get out of 1. a bash, 2. a chroot'ed environment."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:312
msgid "cd /"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:315
msgid ""
"we change to the root dir not to have former access on the device we're "
"about to unmount."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:317
msgid "umount..."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:320
msgid ""
"First we need to unmount the proc device from the loop device, so you can "
"unmount this."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:324
msgid "delete the binding from /dev/loop0 to /tmp/lfs.disk."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:326
msgid "You may now delete lfs.disk, unless you don't want to use it otherwise."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:331
msgid ""
"You could e.g. pipe the disk dump to install over network. If anybody is "
"plan- ning an LFS installation like that I beg you to contact me via IRC in "
"#lfs on irc.linuxfromscratch.org to 1. get further support and 2. let me "
"share your experience."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:333
msgid "Then you can get back to the book (installing grub/lilo and all that stuff)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:338
msgid ""
"Now for those who are using reiserfs and need to make a bootcd to copy the "
"new system over: 1. make a bootdisk (like in the BLFS section), add all "
"utilities you may need (like reiserfsprogs) 2. make a .tar.gz archive of "
"your new LFS (of course after exiting the chrooted environment):"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:342
msgid "cd $LFS mkdir /tmp/lfscd tar czfv /tmp/lfscd/LFS-<version>-<date>.tar.gz"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:344
msgid "Now create an isofs which uses the bootdisk image as El-Torito bootimage:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:350
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"mkdir /tmp/lfscd/boot\n"
"cp <bootimg> /tmp/lfscd/boot\n"
"cd /tmp/lfscd\n"
"mkisofs -r -o /tmp/lfscd.iso -b /tmp/lfscd/boot/<bootimg> \\ \n"
" -c /tmp/lfscd/boot/catalog\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: origin/one-partition-hint.txt:354
msgid ""
"Now use cdrecord to write the iso image on a CD. The LFS on this CD may not "
"run on other Systems, especially older systems will need an cross-compiled "
"version of LFS (see cross-compiling hint)."
msgstr ""

